4:
O light of hope... Bless me with your
warmth...
9:
Just as I thought... Your "magical
abilities" are actually more akin to
supernatural powers.
14:
But... how could that be? I use spells
and incantations.
19:
By nature, the power of light cannot
be grasped. It is free. That's why
you're the only one that has been
able to harness it—you speak its
power into being.
22:
But your uniqueness is exactly why I
invited you here in the first place.
Just keep doing exactly what you're
doing.
27:
But if my power isn't magic that can
be taught... will I really be able to
fulfill my duty here as a teacher?
32:
To be honest, I'm not expecting
much.
43:
You're here to be a breaker of molds.
To destroy the paradigms built up
within these students' minds. Your
job is to turn their worlds upside
down.
46:
But if you insist on behaving like a
"proper" teacher, then I suggest you
think about the source of your light
itself.
57:
I just don't understand! How does a
good teacher destroy their students'
minds?!
61: Uh... You're asking me this... why?
65:
Well, you've been a teacher here
longer than I have, so I thought you
might know a good way.
69:
I'm sorry, I suppose I haven't earned
the right to call myself a teacher
yet... But I want to help the students
no matter what!
76:
There you are, Ms. Phiria! We've been
looking for you!
80: Y-yes! What is it, you two?
83:
We've been dying to ask you
something! Could you take a look at
this?
85:
We've been racking our brains
about how you're able to use both
the power of wind and light, so we've
compiled our theories here. Please,
let us know what you think!
88:
Y-you did?! Well, um... The thing
about that is—
91:
But no matter what we postulate, we
just keep finding contradictions. We
just can't figure it out, so please! Tell
us where we're going wrong!
94:
All right... I'll try. Would you show me
how you channel your magic?
97:
Yes, ma'am! O all-devouring
darkness! Consume and take form!
101:
O light of hope. Rend this world
asunder!
104:
You... destroyed its source? But how?
Considering the fundamental
principles, this doesn't make any
sense...
109:
Well... that's probably because there
is no sense to be made!
116:
The truth is, there is no rhyme or
reason to my powers! They're
free-form!
120:
Wh-what I mean to say is... I'm just
imagining the light as I see it in my
own mind.
124:
Its gentle touch feels like a warm,
cuddly embrace!
129:
But at the same time, it holds the
terrifying power to destroy worlds...
F-for me, at least! This is all just
personal experience!
133:
Oh, no... I've gone and confused
everyone again, haven't I? Um... I'm
so sorry, I...
136:
Don't worry, Ms. Phiria. We're
listening. Why don't you just take a
deep breath?
145:
So what you're saying is that you
envision the magic before you recite
your incantations... and reality
bends to your will?
147:
It sounds like all of this only applies
to you, Ms. Phiria...
151: Yes, right! That's it exactly—I think!
158:
I see what you mean by "free-form"...
But having too much freedom
makes all of this way harder.
162:
Your own world is yours to shape. It's
up to you to decide.
165:
You're free to do as you please. And
if you fail, then you can always start
over and try again. Someone very
important taught me that.
173: And that became my light of hope.
176:
So I want all of you to do the same.
Be free! D-does that make sense?
179:
Maybe this does have some reason
to it after all. Developing new
theories often necessitates
overwriting old ones...
181:
So you're saying that we shouldn't
limit ourselves. That we should be
free to speak our own world into
existence.
185:
Exactly, you mustn't limit yourself!
That's the most important part!
188:
Somehow you two seem more like
teachers than I do...
191:
Or maybe you just don't fit the
typical teacher mold!
193:
Ms. Phiria isn't even that much older
than we are. Maybe that's why?
196:
Clearly, age doesn't have anything
to do with it...
204:
To be honest, we're just starting out.
We still don't understand much of
anything yet.
206:
Please, Ms. Phiria! Break down our
preconceptions so that we can grow!
210: I'll do my best to do just that!
213:
D-does that mean... you want to
hear more of what I have to say?
217:
I'd love to keep meeting you like this,
but while we're at it... do you think
you could help me understand the
textbooks?
220:
I mean, of course... I never thought
WE'D be the ones teaching YOU the
reading material, though!
224:
Well, then we might as well break
down that preconception first!
228:
So... there you have it! That's the trick
to harnessing light!
231:
Ms. Phiria really is just flying by the
seat of her pants with these
lectures...
234: Oh! I think I'm getting the hang of it.
239:
See? You did it! Keep at it, everyone!
Break down the world you knew
before so that you can rebuild it
your own way!
243:
Didn't see that coming... She's
actually got a knack for this!
247:
Sure looks like fun. I'm glad she's
doing so well.
252:
As am I. It looks like she's going to
thrive here.
